This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of natural language processing (cs.CL) because it introduces a large corpus for sarcasm research and sarcasm detection, which is a subfield of natural language processing. It is also likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories because the corpus is used for training and evaluating systems for sarcasm detection. Additionally, the paper provides user and conversation context, which suggests that it may also belong to the social and information networks (cs.SI) sub-category. Finally, the paper may also belong to the cybernetics (cs.CY) sub-category because it deals with the study of communication and control in the animal and the machine.
